Loan Data Exploration¶

by (Andrew Samy Hanna)¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This document explores a dataset containing 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

This document explores a dataset containing 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in features affect the loan amount , features affect the loans outcome status and features used for predicting the borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR) for the loan.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I think features like: ( EmploymentStatusDuration - Term - MonthlyLoanPayment - StatedMonthlyIncome - ProsperScore - IsBorrowerHomeowner - AvailableBankcardCredit - Recommendations) will have a grear effect on my investigation

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

I found that:¶

Most of loans are taken by employed.

Employment Duration is inversely proportional with the number of loans.

The distribution of APR has a large peak around 0.2, then a smaller one around 0.28 and there is a very high number of loans (more than 7000) with APR between 0.34 and 0.36.

The distribution of Monthly Loan Payment has a large peak around 250, then a smaller one around 500, then a verry small peak around 850 and there is a very high number of loans (more than 11000) with Monthly Loan Payment between 170 and 180.

Most of the Loan Amounts are multiples of 5000: ( 5000 - 10000 - 15000 - 20000 - 25000 )

Most loans length were 36 months.

Most of loans are taken by the borrowers with monthly income around 5000

The ProsperScore of most of the loans is between 4 and 8.

Available Bank card Credit is inversely proportional with the number of loans

More than 90% of loans without any Recommendations

Being a Homeowner has no effect as both distributions nearly the same

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The distribution of (the Monthly Loan Payment , stated monthly income and Available Bank card Credit) was surprising at the first plotting.Then by using a smaller range (to zoom in and remove unusual points from plots), the distribution became much better.
